The article discusses the My Brother's Keeper initiative launched by President Obama to address the opportunity gap for boys and young men of color. The initiative aims to determine what works to help young people reach their full potential and recommends actions to remove barriers to their success. The article highlights the importance of mentorship and calls on Americans to sign up as long-term mentors. It also presents the 90-day report of the Presidential Task Force, which includes recommendations for various stages of a young person's life, such as getting a healthy start, reading at grade level by third grade, graduating from high school, completing post-secondary education or training, entering the workforce, and reducing violence and providing second chances. The Task Force emphasizes the need for comprehensive approaches that address the educational, physical, social, and emotional needs of young people. The article also mentions the commitment of leading foundations to invest at least $200 million to support the initiative.